qx|Resp,wide|bt||cs|6|ht|b|fp|1|at|^-{           Responding to 2@C Opening          }
^-|FP||VA|4|AT|^B@2^*BMM: ^*NAgain, there are many schemes for responding to 2@C, but we review only the 2@D waiting which is the most popular and straightforward. Responder may have range of hands from a few points to enough that slam is likely. One point is clear. If partner opens 2@C, responder may not pass below game except if it goes 2@C-P-2@D-P-2N, and even then only with 0 to a bad 2 and no 5-card major. Basically 2@C establishes a game force. There are other rare occasions, we will look at them later, when with less than 3 points responder may pass below game. |
PG| ***** 30 ***** |


AT|

Adopting 2@D waiting response, responder bids 2@D first then for his second response, with a good hand he makes a positive bid and with three points or less he makes a negative bid.|
PG| ***** 31 ***** |


AT|

Responder, using an adjunct scheme, can bypass initial 2@D response when his hand is strong enough where he would have made a positive second bid after a 2@D waiting first bid. An initial positive response requires 8+ points. Those first positive response are 2@H, 2@S, 2N 3@C, or 3@D. 2N shows a balanced hand.|
PG| ***** 32 ***** |


AT|

^B@2^*BMM: ^*NHoward has additional note regarding initial response of 3@C or 3@D, "I would tend to avoid bidding 3@C or 3@D over a 2@C opener, even if responder has the requirements to do so (5-card suit with 2 of top 3 or 6+ card suit with 2 of top 4). It takes up too much room. Bidding 2@D and then hearing why opener opened 2@C usually results in a much better auction."|
PG| ***** 33 ***** |


AT|

Next, let us put a spot light on couple important issues by looking at some examples.|
